\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}


Throughout this paper all graphs are simple with no loops and multiple edges.
Let $G$ be a graph. We denote the vertex set and the edge set of $G$, by $V(G)$ and $E(G)$, respectively. For $v\in V(G)$, $E_v$ denotes the set of
 all edges incident to $v$. A {\it  $k$-vertex coloring} of $G$ is an assignment of $k$ colors to the vertices of $G$. This coloring is said to be {\it proper} if no two adjacent vertices have the same color. In this paper, we only consider proper vertex colorings; thus, whenever we say "vertex coloring" we mean a proper vertex coloring even if it is not stated explicitly. A $k$-vertex coloring of a  graph $G$ is a partition $(V_1, \ldots, V_k)$ of $V(G)$ into $k$ independent  sets called {\it color classes}.  The {\it chromatic number} $\chi(G) $ of $G$ is the minimum $k$ for which $G$ is $k$-vertex colorable.  A {\it $k$-edge coloring} of $G$ is an assignment of $k$ colors to the edges of $G$; it is said to be {\it proper} if two edges with a common end-point do not have the same color, and {\it improper} if it is not necessarily proper. The minimum $k$ such that $G$ admits a proper $k$-edge coloring is the {\it chromatic index} of $G$ and denoted by $\chi'(G)$. A {\it $k$-clique} is a set of $k$ vertices inducing a complete graph. A {\it walk} in $G$ is a  sequence $W=v_0e_1v_1e_2v_2 \ldots, e_kv_k$, whose terms are alternately vertices and edges, such that $e_i=v_{i-1}v_i$, for $1\leq i \leq k$. The number $k$ is called the length of the walk. A walk is called a {\it closed walk} if $v_0=v_k$.
We denote the path and the cycle of order $n$ by $P_n$ and $C_n$, respectively. Also, by $K_n$, we mean the complete graph of order $n$. The reader is referred to~\cite{golumbic} for all definitions in graph theory which are not defined here.


