In this paper we investigate the improper twin edge chromatic index of graphs which was, to the best of our knowledge, not introduced before. We show that for every graph $G$ whose each component has order at least $3$, $\chi(G)\leq \chi'_{it}(G)\leq \chi(G)+1$. Our proof is constructive in the sense that for any graph $G$, if we know an optimal vertex coloring of it, then it provides an improper twin $(\chi(G)+1)$-edge coloring of $G$ (which induces the given $\chi(G)$-vertex coloring). Our characterisation emphasizes   the closely related problem  of deciding whether all color classes are of  odd size in all optimal colorings. We use this new problem to show that it is NP-complete to decide whether $\chi'_{it}(G)= \chi(G)$ even when the graph $G$ is restricted to have $\chi(G)$ equal to its maximum clique size and in the bounded degree case.   
Finally, we give first examples of graph classes for which this question can be decided in polynomial time. These classes include bipartite graphs, split graphs, co-chordal graphs and co-comparability graphs with bounded chromatic number. 








