In what follows, we show that the improper twin chromatic index of bipartite graphs do not exceed 3, again  using an intermediary result about trees.

\begin{lem}\label{thm:tree3}
If $T\neq P_2$ is a tree, then $\chi'_{it}(T)\leq 3$. Moreover, there is an improper twin edge coloring of $T$ with $3$ colors $\{0,1,2\}$ such that the following hold:
\begin{enumerate}
\item[i)] There are at most two vertices with color $2$ and they are in the same part of the bipartition.
\item[ii)]  There are  no two vertices with color $0$ (respectively $1$) in the different parts of the bipartition.
\end{enumerate}
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
 Consider a rooted tree $T$ with root $v$ of degree at least 2. Set $c(x)=0$ for all $x \in N(v)$ and set the colors of the vertices in each level of the tree rooted at $v$ alternatively by 1 and 0. Now, starting from the deepest level, color the edges of $T$ by 0 and 1 to ensure the colors set for vertices; note that this is always possible by choosing the colors appropriately. Let $a,b,c, \ldots$ be the colors (among $0,1$ and $2$) of the edges $e_1, e_2,e_3, \ldots$ incident to $v$. If $a+b+c+ \cdots = 1 \mbox{ or } 2 \pmod 3$, then this is an improper twin 3-edge coloring of $T$ where color 2 is used at most once, and therefore statements $(i)$ and $(ii)$ are satisfied. If $a+b+c+ \cdots = 0 \pmod 3$, then change the color of edge $e_1=vx_1$ from $a$ to $a+2 \pmod 3$ and the color of edge $e_2=vx_2$ from $b$ to $b+2 \pmod 3$. Now,  $c(x_1)=c(x_2)=2$ and $c(v)=1$ and this is an improper twin $3$-edge coloring of $T$, where one part of the bipartition is colored by 1 and the other part by 0 except two vertices, namely $x_1$ and $x_2$ which are colored by 2.
\end{proof}

\begin{thm}\label{thm:bip3}
Let $B=(X,Y,E)$ be a bipartite graph, then $\chi'_{it}(B)\leq 3$.
\end{thm}

\begin{proof}
We first note that it suffices to prove the statement for connected graphs. Consider a spanning tree $T$ of $B$ and obtain an improper twin $3$-edge coloring of $T$ as described in Lemma \ref{thm:tree3}. Giving color 0 to all edges in $E(B)\setminus E(T)$ yields an improper twin 3-edge coloring of $B$.
\end{proof}

Theorems \ref{thm:bip2} and  \ref{thm:bip3} summarize the improper twin chromatic index of bipartite graphs as follows:

\begin{cor}\label{cor:bip}
Let $B=(X,Y,E)$ be a connected bipartite graph, then $\chi'_{it}(B) = 3$ if and only if both $X$ and $Y$ have odd size, and $\chi'_{it}(B) = 2$ otherwise. Moreover, this can be checked in constant time if $B$ is given with its bipartition $(X,Y)$.
\end{cor}

One can also note that, it follows from Lemma \ref{thm:tree3} that if $\chi'_{it}(B) = 3$, then there is an improper twin 3-edge coloring of $B$ such that color 2 appears at most twice in one part and no color 0 (respectively 1) appears in different parts.





\section{Bounds on the Improper Twin Edge Chromatic Index}\label{sec:general}

In this section, we show that $\chi(G) \leq \chi'_{it}(G)\leq \chi(G)+1$ holds for general graphs. In particular, Theorem \ref{thm:odd} of this section is the generalization of Theorems \ref{thm:bip2} and  \ref{thm:bip3} to general graphs. Indeed, for a connected bipartite graph $B=(X,Y,E)$, we have $\chi(B)=2 \pmod 4$ and Theorems \ref{thm:bip2} and  \ref{thm:bip3} imply that we have $\chi'_{it}(B)=\chi(B)+1$ if and only if both $X$ and $Y$ have odd cardinalities; this is exactly Theorem \ref{thm:odd} (ii) for bipartite graphs. However, it should be noted that although the use of a spanning tree to set the colors of each vertex is the same as in the bipartite case, the technique of closed odd walk used in the general case requires that the graph is not bipartite. Therefore, the bipartite case in Section \ref{sec:specialcases} is not directly implied by our general result and requires a separate proof.

\begin{thm}\label{oddc} If $G$ is a graph with an odd vertex chromatic number more than $1$, then $\chi'_{it}(G)=\chi(G)$.
\end{thm}
\begin{proof}
We assume without loss of generality that $G$ is connected since otherwise the same proof applies to every connected component. Let $f$ be a $k$-vertex coloring of $G$ where $k=\chi(G)$. We show that there is an improper twin edge coloring $s$ of $G$ using exactly $k$ colors, where $c(v_i)=f(v_i)$ for all vertices $v_i \in V(G), i=1,\ldots, n$. Without loss of generality assume that $v_1$ is a vertex of $G$ such that $f(v_1)=0$ and  $T$ is a spanning tree of $G$ with root $v_1$. Now, color the edges of $T$ from deepest level to the first level so that the vertex coloring induced by this edge coloring ensures  $c(v_i)=f(v_i)$ for all vertices $v_i \in V(G), i\geq 2$; note that this is always possible since we are proceeding the edges from the last level to the first. Then, color all edges in $E(G)\setminus E(T)$ by 0. Now, let $a,b,c, \ldots$ be the colors (among $[0,k-1]$) of the edges in $E(T)$ incident to $v_1$. Then we have $c(v_1)= a+b+c+ \cdots \pmod k$. If $c(v_1) = 0 \pmod k$, then this is an improper twin $k$-edge coloring of $G$. Otherwise, we apply the following technique to obtain a new  improper twin $k$-edge coloring $s'$ inducing a $k$-vertex coloring $c'$,  where $c'(v_i)=c(v_i), i=2,\ldots, n$ and $c'(v_1)=0$.

We claim that there exists a closed walk of odd length passing by $v_1$. Since $\chi(G)>2$, the graph $G$ contains an odd cycle. Consider an odd cycle $C$ in $G$. Since $G$ is connected, there exists a path between $v_1$ and $C$, say $P$. Traverse $P$ starting at $v_1$ and go to $C$ and then traverse $C$ and then come back to $v_1$ via $P$, to obtain an odd closed walk passing by $v_1$. Note that each edge of $P$ is traversed twice. The claim is proved.

 Now, add alternately $+x, -x \pmod k$ to $s(e)$,  for each $e$ in this odd walk starting from $v_1$. All vertices except $v_1$ have $c'(v_i)=c(v_i)$ since the summation of the colors of edges incident to $v_i$ is the same for all $i=2,\ldots, n $, and $c'(v_1)= 2x + c(v_1) \pmod k$. Since $k$ is odd, the equation $2x + c(v_1)=0 \pmod k$ has a solution in $\mathbb{Z}_k$. The proof is complete.
 \end{proof}

